# Linux
Basic Linux Commands
pwd #The pwd command is used to display the location of the current working directory
mkdir <directory name> #The mkdir command is used to create a new directory under any directory.
rmdir <directory name> #The rmdir command is used to delete a directory.
ls #The ls command is used to display a list of content of a directory.
cd <directory name> #The cd command is used to change the current directory.
touch <file name> 
touch <file1>  <file2> ....  #The touch command is used to create empty files. We can create multiple empty files by executing it once.
cat <file name> #To create a file, execute it as follows
cp <existing file name> <new file name> #To copy in the same directory
mv <file name> <directory path> #The mv command is used to move a file or a directory form one location to another location
rename 's/old-name/new-name/' files #The rename command is used to rename files. It is useful for renaming a large group of files
head <file name> #The head command is used to display the content of a file. It displays the first 10 lines of a file
tail <file name> #The tail command is similar to the head command. The difference between both commands is that it displays the last ten lines of the file content. It is useful for reading the error message
more <file name> #The only difference between both cat & more commands is that, in case of larger files, the more command displays screenful output at a time
su <user name> #The su command provides administrative access to another user
useradd  username #The useradd command is used to add or remove a user on a Linux server.
zip, unzip #Use zip to compress files into a zip archive, and unzip to extract files from a zip archive.
hostname #Use hostname to know your name in your host or network. Basically, it displays your hostname and IP address.
